XVII. 1. a. Nominatae jam. It had already been decided where the consuls were to be employed. The particular province of each was either decided by lot, as in the pre-- sent case, or they might come to an agreement among themselves. In after times, by a law of C. Gracchus, it was provided that the consular provinces should always be determined before the election of the consuls took place.

b. Cornelio, Publius Cornelius Scipio, son of L. Scipio, who had been consul in the sixth year of the first Punic war. He was killed in Spain, together with his brother Cnaeus, near Castulo, in the eighth year of his command there, B.c. 211, (inf. xxV. 34, 35).
